dev.marksman.collectionviews

Interface NonEmptyVector<A>

  • Type Parameters:
    A - the element type
    All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<A>, NonEmptyIterable<A>, java.util.RandomAccess, Vector<A>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    ImmutableNonEmptyVector<A>

    public interface NonEmptyVector<A>
extends NonEmptyIterable<A>, Vector<A>
    A Vector that is guaranteed at compile-time to contain at least one element.

    In addition to guarantees of Vector, provides the following benefits:

    • NonEmptyIterable.head() method that returns the first element.
    • Implements NonEmptyIterable.
    • fmap(com.jnape.palatable.lambda.functions.Fn1<? super A, ? extends B>) always returns a NonEmptyVector.

      • fmap

        default <B> NonEmptyVector<B> fmap(com.jnape.palatable.lambda.functions.Fn1<? super A,? extends B> f)
        Maps a function over the elements in a NonEmptyVector and returns a new NonEmptyVector of the same size (but possibly a different type).

        Does not make any copies of underlying data structures.

        This method is stack-safe, so a Vector can be mapped as many times as the heap permits.

        Specified by:

      • tryWrap

        static <A> com.jnape.palatable.lambda.adt.Maybe<NonEmptyVector<A>> tryWrap(A[] underlying)
        Attempts to create a NonEmptyVector that wraps an array.

        Does not make any copies of the given array. The NonEmptyVector will hold on to a reference to the array, but will never alter it in any way.

        Since bearers of this NonEmptyVector will be unable to mutate or gain access to the underlying array, it is safe to share.

        Since this does not make a copy of the array, be aware that anyone that holds a direct reference to the array can still mutate it. Use Vector.copyFrom(java.lang.Iterable<A>) instead if you want to avoid this situation.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        underlying - array to wrap
        Returns:
        a NonEmptyVector<A> wrapped in a Maybe.just(A) if underlying is non-empty; Maybe.nothing() otherwise.

      • tryCopyFrom

        static <A> com.jnape.palatable.lambda.adt.Maybe<ImmutableNonEmptyVector<A>> tryCopyFrom(int maxCount,
                                                                                        java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Attempts to construct a new ImmutableNonEmptyVector from any Iterable, but consuming a maximum number of elements.

        If determined to be non-empty, the Iterable will be eagerly iterated, but only up to a maximum of maxCount elements. If maxCount elements are not available, then the all of the elements available will be returned.

        This method will make a copy of the data provided, unless source is an ImmutableVector and its size is less than or equal to maxCount, in which case it will be returned directly.

        If source is an ImmutableVector that is greater than maxCount in size, a copy will always be made, therefore making it memory-safe to take a small slice of a huge Vector that you no longer need.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        maxCount - the maximum number of elements to consume from the source. Must be >= 0. If 0, this method will always return Maybe.nothing().
        source - an Iterable<A> that will be iterated eagerly for up to maxCount elements. It is safe for source to be infinite.
        Returns:
        an ImmutableNonEmptyVector<A> wrapped in a Maybe.just(A) if source is non-empty; Maybe.nothing() otherwise.

      • copyFromOrThrow

        static <A> ImmutableNonEmptyVector<A> copyFromOrThrow(int maxCount,
                                                      java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Attempts to construct a new ImmutableNonEmptyVector from any Iterable, but consuming a maximum number of elements. If the Iterable is empty, throws an IllegalArgumentException.

        If determined to be non-empty, the Iterable will be eagerly iterated, but only up to a maximum of maxCount elements. If maxCount elements are not available, then the all of the elements available will be returned.

        This method will make a copy of the data provided, unless source is an ImmutableVector and its size is less than or equal to maxCount, in which case it will be returned directly.

        If source is an ImmutableVector that is greater than maxCount in size, a copy will always be made, therefore making it memory-safe to take a small slice of a huge Vector that you no longer need.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        maxCount - the maximum number of elements to consume from the source. Must be >= 1.
        source - an Iterable<A> that will be iterated eagerly for up to maxCount elements. It is safe for source to be infinite.
        Returns:
        an ImmutableNonEmptyVector<A>
